If you want to reproduce again, you'll need to clean and rebuild.

**Impact**:
Because of this warning, pipelines are failing and the workaround is needed.

**Workaround**:
Just replace the if with (add null-forgiving operator):
```
if (!string.IsNullOrEmpty(s))
{
        yield return s!;
}
```

This shouldn't be needed, as the string.IsNullOrEmpty is already ensuring that the string is not null. (and working for other target frameworks)

**Version Used**: .NET 8.0

**Steps to Reproduce**:

Use or construct a type that implements both a collection interface (`IEnumerable` and `void Add(object? value)` at least) and `IDisposable`. Initialize an instance in a using statement (either kind).

For example, I used [`MultipartFormDataContent`](https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/api/system.net.http.multipartformdatacontent?view=net-8.0):

```csharp
using var form = new MultipartFormDataContent();
form.Add(new StringContent(request.Id.ToString()), "id");
form.Add(new StringContent(request.Name), "name");
form.Add(new StringContent(request.Email), "email");
form.Add(new StringContent(request.Fingerprint), "fingerprint");
form.Add(new StringContent(request.ExpiresOn.ToString()), "expiresOn");
```

But this does it too:

```csharp
public class DontDoThis : IEnumerable
{
    public void Add(object? value)
    {
    }
    IEnumerator IEnumerable.GetEnumerator()
    {
        yield break;
    }
}
```

**Diagnostic Id**:

IDE0028: Use collection initializers or expressions

**Expected Behavior**:

IDE0028 should see that the type is disposable and initialized in a using statement and avoid suggesting the code change. Similar to IDE0017: Use object initializers. See comments here: https://github.com/dotnet/roslyn/issues/77365#issuecomment-2687530003

**Actual Behavior**:

The analyzer fires on the code example (above) and suggests this unsafe code:

```csharp
using var form = new MultipartFormDataContent
{
    { new StringContent(request.Id.ToString()), "id" },
    { new StringContent(request.Name), "name" },
    { new StringContent(request.Email), "email" },
    { new StringContent(request.Fingerprint), "fingerprint" },
    { new StringContent(request.ExpiresOn.ToString()), "expiresOn" }
};
```

